SIMPLE: relic
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Relic
<hw>Rel"ic</hw> <pr>(r?l"?k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>relique</ets>, from L. <ets>reliquiae</ets>, pl., akin to
<ets>relinquere</ets> to leave behind. See <er>Relinquish</er>.]</ety>
<altsp>[Formerly written also <asp>relique</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>That which remains; that which is left after loss or decay; a
remaining portion; a remnant.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.
Wyclif.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>relics</qex> of lost innocence.</q>
<rj><qau>Kebe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fragments, scraps, the bits and greasy <qex>relics</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The body from which the soul has departed; a corpse;
especially, the body, or some part of the body, of a deceased saint or
martyr; -- usually in the plural when referring to the whole
body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There are very few treasuries of <qex>relics</qex> in Italy that
have not a tooth or a bone of this saint.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy <qex>relics</qex>, Rowe, to this fair urn we trust,⟦br⟧
And sacred place by Dryden's awful dust.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, a memorial; anything preserved in
remembrance; <as>as, <ex>relics</ex> of youthful days or
friendships</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pearls were spilt;⟦br⟧
Some lost, some stolen, some as <qex>relics</qex> kept.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Relicly</ent>⟦br⟧
